list is n.\n1 <= n <= 104\n0 <= Node.val < n\nAll the values Node.val are unique.\n1 <= nums.length <= n\n0 <= nums[i] < n\nAll the values of nums are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\n# Definition for singly-linked list.\n# class ListNode:\n#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n#         self.val = val\n#         self.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def numComponents(self, head: Optional[ListNode], nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\n# Definition for singly-linked list.\n# class ListNode:\n#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n#         self.val = val\n#         self.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def numComponents(self, head: Optional[ListNode], nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        num_set = set(nums)\n        connected_components = 0\n        in_component = False\n        \n        current = head\n        while current:\n            if current.val in num_set:\n                if not in_component:\n                    # Start of a new component\n                    connected_components += 1\n                    in_component = True\n            else:\n                in_component = False\n            \n            current = current.next\n        \n        return connected_components\n```\n\nThis solution works by iterating through the linked list and using a set for quick lookup to determine if the current node's value is in `nums`. It keeps track of whether it is currently in a component using the `in_component` flag. When it encounters a value from `nums` and is not already in a component, it increments the count of connected components.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}